label chapter8:

    # [Scene: Harborfront Lane | Late Morning — Three Months After the Amendment Signing]

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant, metallic thump of pile drivers; gulls have gone quieter, their calls thin]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, mournful strings — sustained, each note a small ache]
    "You signed the pilot amendment with a pen that felt too light for what it bound. The legal language was precise and beautiful in its way, like a map that forgot to show a few of"
    "the roads you needed. Cass stood beside you as cameras circled, flattering light stroking the angles of their face; on the table, the scale model of Harborfront glinted under a plastic dome, tiny pilings rising in"
    "neat rows."
    show cass_adler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cass_adler "This will protect the town, Maya. It's the compromise we needed to get traction."
    "Their smile is quick, practiced. Their hand finds yours for a beat — old rhythms folded into new agreements."
    "You remember the way the mayor's pen hesitated, how Eli's jaw tightened from the back of the room until it nearly cracked. At the moment of signing, you felt a thrill — relief, at first. Money"
    "would flow. Jobs would come. Boards that once splintered in storms would be raised; kids would cross new elevated walkways without wet sneakers."
    show mayor_jonah_cruz at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_jonah_cruz "Funding starts next quarter. We'll begin with the southeast docks and move north."
    "He taps the printed schedule with the brass of the town seal reflecting like a small sun."

    cass_adler "Local hiring protocols are in the plan. We'll prioritize—"
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "Prioritize promises in a glossy brochure doesn't keep a boat from rotting."
    "The exchange is sharp and public; you steady the conversation, measure tone. You had thought, then, you had chosen the least terrible path. You had believed the money could be yanked toward community control. You had"
    "believed, perhaps selfishly, that your signature could be the lever that kept both people and marsh intact."

    menu:
        "Step forward to answer the crowd's questions":
            "You raise your hand and speak to the gathered townspeople, pointing out pilot safeguards and community oversight measures; the applause is cautious."
        "Stay beside Cass, letting them lead":
            "You let Cass's confidence carry the moment; their words land like varnish on the boardwalk — sleek, persuasive — and you feel both relieved and slightly invisible."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "For the next few weeks the town learns a new rhythm: trucks at dawn, scaffold shadows on the sand, billboards promising a 'Resilient Harbor — Local Jobs, Lasting Security.' Aquila's logos bloom on plywood sheets. There"
    "are people who clap when the first new pilings go up — cousins, former fishermen, kids whose parents will get temp work — and there are people who watch with folding arms and folded histories."
    # [Scene: Construction Site — Edge of the Marsh | Afternoon]
    hide cass_adler
    hide mayor_jonah_cruz
    hide eli_navarro

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The machine's relentless thud; diesel engines, the occasional shouted instruction]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A distant piano pattern that never resolves]
    "When the first heavy machinery comes to the marsh edge, the smell changes. Diesel cuts through the salt, and the earth makes a raw, wet sound like old bone being sanded. Volunteer crews work next to"
    "armored contractors; an Aquila foreman tapes an updated shoreline elevation to a post as if elevation numbers could be the same as memory."
    show cass_adler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cass_adler "These living-shoreline strips will, in time, knit the tides to the shore. Marsh grasses planted with engineered substrates — it's science you trust."
    "They tilt a tablet toward you, showing a simulation of waves curling harmlessly against an elegant seawall."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Science that changes who decides where those seams are sewn is different."
    "You watch a small, perfect oystercatcher hop from stone to stone in the model; in real life the birds are easier to scare now."

    cass_adler "You're reading this as loss because you know the town as it once was. I'm trying to scale protection so everyone can stay."
    "Their voice is generous with logic and low on apology. You want to believe them. You want to believe that scale needn't eat the small things the town cherishes. But the machines do not distinguish between what is measurable and what is beloved."

    menu:
        "Walk the new elevated boardwalk, touching the rails":
            "You run a hand along the raised plank; it is smooth and new, engineered to last. A little girl skitters past, laughing, and you feel a tiny, guilty warmth."
        "Descend to the mudflats to inspect the old dock's remains":
            "You pick your way across slick wood and barnacle, fingers catching on rusted nails. The century-old joint that once bore a hundred stories gives under your foot, and your stomach drops as if the town shifted beneath you."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    # [Scene: Mayor's Temporary Office — Harborfront Lane | Late Afternoon]
    hide cass_adler
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low office hum; television muted to a news feed that shows smiling contractors]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single cello line, steadying but slightly dissonant]
    show mayor_jonah_cruz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_jonah_cruz "We secured emergency funds, Maya. This could have been a worse deal. We have protections for tenants, relocation allowances, a community oversight board."
    "He speaks like he has counted the costs and decided which teeth are worth keeping."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Oversight that answers to an easement trust is different from control."
    "The words leave you like pebbles dropped into a well; they sink with an echo you can't exactly name."

    mayor_jonah_cruz "The trust gives Aquila long-term decision power. It's how they guarantee investment."
    "He looks at you as if by explaining the mechanism the moral unreality might become easier to bear."
    "Legal clauses are not storm surges — they creep. They arrive in letters, in terms you sign at midnight because the alternative looks like nothing at all. The pilot brings a few weeks of paychecks and"
    "then letters that read like waves: easements here, decision transfers there. Small docks are mapped for removal. Names of old families are circled in blue ink. There is a phrase that repeats on Aquila's memos: 'optimal"
    "reconfiguration.' For engineers it is elegant. For people whose lives are patterned by the old angles of the shore, it feels like erasure."
    # [Scene: Lowtide Marsh — Dusk]
    hide mayor_jonah_cruz
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A hush where birds used to argue; an occasional far-off sonic beep from machinery]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano and an undertow of synthetic pads]
    "You walk the marsh alone one dusk, boots catching in mud, the leather of your notebook damp. You keep a mental checklist of species sightings and can't reconcile the empty spaces: where you once found fiddler"
    "crabs stacking tiny sand towers, you find muddy scars. Where shoals of minnows used to flip silver, there are shallow, heated puddles that reflect light like small wounds."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "We didn't all sign on to lose the docks, Maya."
    "He comes up behind you without a footstep; his voice is low, the harbor wind taking the rest."
    "He stands a arm's-length away, an island of solidness. He smells of salt and tar and the precise, human smell of someone who has worked with their hands for years. You take him in — the set of his shoulders, the way his hands are steady but not still."

    eli_navarro "You thought you'd keep the town afloat by leaning into Aquila. Maybe you did — temporarily. But at what cost? Who gets to decide which families keep their moorings when the trust says otherwise?"
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "I thought I could steer it. I thought a pilot could bind them to our oversight."
    "You taste the old ghost of your failed forecast — that same, small self that learned to doubt. 'I wanted to save as much as I could.'"

    eli_navarro "And you did what you thought was best. But signing something that shifts control — that's not saving the town as it is. It's saving it as a safer version of someone else's design."
    "His words are not accusation only; there's grief in them, and a practical ache for the docks, the boats, the names carved on planks."

    maya_rios "Do you think I wanted to sign away people's rights? Do you think I liked that clause about easements? I fought for language that would give the town seats at the trust table. I —"
    "Your voice catches. You find yourself cataloging every small negotiation that felt like a victory at the time, and how each felt less real in the light of the removal notices."

    eli_navarro "I know you fought. I know you argued in the room."
    "He steps closer now, and the closeness is charged with a dozen shared years. 'But fighting inside that machine changes you, Maya. Sometimes it makes promises sound like instruments.'"
    "There is a hard silence between you. The marsh's breath seems to harden, temporary and brittle as the pilings out past the breaker. You want to tell him the calculus you ran, the nights tearing through"
    "models, the sleeplessness that made arguments appear sharper in your head. Instead, you let the silence speak what the words won't: that compromise often tastes like ash, and ash is all that lingers when the flame"
    "has burned the old shapes away."

    menu:
        "Reach for Eli's hand":
            "You take his fingers, seeking warmth; he closes his hand around yours with a small, sad smile, and for a moment the world steadies, the rigs receding to a thin line on the horizon."
        "Step back to the high grass and keep looking at the tide":
            "You step back into the marsh grasses, eyes on the water. Eli watches you, respect and sorrow mingled on his face, and you both hold a distance that feels like an unspoken promise and a boundary."

