    "Continue"
    # [Scene: Harborfront Lane — Evening — Public Forum]
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Murmur of people, a child's laughter cut by the rasp of a speaker's voice]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minor-key violin, quiet but insistent]
    "Public forums become sessions of grief and inventory. Those who took early jobs speak of wages and immediate bills met. Those whose family slips are slated for removal list the names of boats and anchors. Ivy"
    "organizes petitions. The local paper runs profiles of families forced to relocate or accept buyouts. Aquila runs op-eds about 'resilience metrics' and ecosystem engineering."
    show cass_adler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cass_adler "We can refine allocations. This is iteration, Maya—policy evolves."
    "They stand at the front, hands poised like someone offering plaster for a fractured bone."
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "Iteration that erases the old pier isn't the same as progress."
    "You say softly, but several people lean in; someone murmurs agreement. 'We have to hold onto the marsh's shape, not just make it tolerable.'"

    cass_adler "Holding onto shape is romantic, but it doesn't shield against the storms we see coming."
    "Their reply is polite, then weary. 'I thought we could do both.'"
    "You remember your promise to the marsh in the earliest chapters of your life — to listen, to translate, to fight with facts and tenderness. You also remember the practicalities: families who needed immediate cash, basements"
    "that would no longer flood. Your signature had been a lever. It had tilted things. It bought breathing room for some and began a slow compression of others."
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You made a choice,' he says later, offstage from the meeting, voice small over the clang of folding chairs. 'I can stand with you if you want me to. But I can't stand by Aquila's right to redraw our shore."

    maya_rios "You don't have to choose me over the town. I wouldn't ask that."
    "You mean it; your work is never only about you."
    "That night you sit at the old dock that still remains, the grain of the wood rough under your knees. Above, the sky is a bruise, the harbor lights smeared into soft gold. The town is"
    "quieter than it used to be; laughter is trimmed like a hedge. The pilings hum at a frequency you wish you could fine-tune."
    # [Scene: Lowtide Marsh — Dawn — Weeks Later]
    hide cass_adler
    hide maya_rios
    hide eli_navarro

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft, hopeful scrape of a trowel; a gull calls, tentative]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, low piano motif that holds a note of fragile resolve]
    "Time has put its slow, steady pressure on your choice. There are mornings of small, undeniable grace: neighbors hired through Aquila's local promise give their first paychecks to families, kids return to safer boardwalks, and a"
    "patchwork of restored spartina looks, from one angle, like protection knitting itself to the shore."
    "But there are also lists and maps that will not let you forget: easements signed for decades; a trust with legal control; an old family dock dismantled for 'optimal slope.' Biodiversity charts you audit show the"
    "dip — a measurable decline in certain invertebrates after heavy machinery tamped the mudflat layers. The living-shoreline strips work in principle but displace behaviors the town held sacred: low-tide harvests at moonrise, late-night boat songs, names"
    "of benches carved by hands now working for a company that answers to shareholders."
    "You count the wins in spreadsheets and losses in the spaces they used to fill. Your laboratory notebooks full of tide notes have a new entry now: the cost of trade-offs. You had hoped to keep"
    "both the people and the place. You had not imagined how many intangible seams a contract could tug loose."
    show maya_rios at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "I convinced myself the amendment was a bridge."
    "You whisper this to no one; the harbor swallows your words. 'I thought I could bind them into partnership.'"
    "The victory is heavy with consequence. The frequent storms are quieter; the big surges cause less immediate damage. People sleep with fewer dread-filled dreams of the sea taking a house in the night. Lives are stabilized"
    "in the ways that counting money can stabilize them. Still, when you stand at the water's edge, and the skyline of Harborfront is a row of cranes and engineered seawalls like teeth, you feel an ache"
    "that isn't soothed by safety."
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant pile driver pings once, like a tiny, repeating bell]
    "There are things you have preserved. There are things you have allowed to change irrevocably. You have done what you believed would spare as many as possible — and yet the map has changed. The town's hush is not the same as peace."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "I can't get the old boards back. I can't put back the names carved into them."
    "He stands beside you now, distance both shared and maintained. 'But I can protect what we still have. I don't know if what you did was right, Maya. I know it was a choice you carried alone when you signed.'"
    show maya_rios at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_rios "I carried it with the belief it would be the best of bad options."
    "You look out at Aquila's logo painted on a temporary wall, corporate letters bright as a promise. 'I've made peace with some parts. Others keep returning to me in the dark.'"
    "There is no neat reconciliation for the gap between saving lives and saving shapes. The amendment brought a tangible shelter from storms and a slow, bureaucratic erosion of how life had been made and named along"
    "the water. For some, the improved safety outweighs the loss. For others, the loss is the point: the shape of their life, the exact angle of the pier, the bowl where boats were moored — gone"
    "or altered beyond recognition."
    hide eli_navarro
    hide maya_rios

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_8 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The water's soft insistence; strings resolve into a single, long note]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Somber strings, then thinning to silence]
    "You stand at the edge of what you saved and what you gave away. You think of your grandmother's locket, of the small bronze piece you carry that remembers shape and salt in a way law"
    "never will. You think of the townspeople who have new paychecks, and the ones who have to retrace family histories in a landscape that has shifted underfoot."
    "You have compromised and won and lost in equal and unequal parts. The tide of consequences continues to roll. You can point to data and to lives stabilized, but you cannot stitch back the exactness of every memory the shore once held."

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings fade out; a single piano note lingers and dies]

    scene bg ch6_f99e88_10 at full_bg
    "THE END"
